message: A Gazan journalist: The Shifaa hospital complex in Gaza City has become a home for stray dogs, walking among the graves...
Palestinian channels publish a photo of what they claim was the vehicle (and ladders) used by the Israeli special forces yesterday in the operation that freed the hostages.

A closer look at one of the houses in the Nuseirat "camp" where part of the hostages were kept

A Gazan journalist shows the remains of a truck he claims was used by Israeli special forces in yesterday's hostage rescue operation.

At 00:25 of the video he points to the remains of the truck. According to him, the forces destroyed the truck before leaving the scene.

At 00:35 the journalist points to one of the buildings where the hostages were (the hostages were rescued from two different locations - AA), which was apparently attacked from the air after the rescue.

A Gazan journalist gives a tour of the route taken by part of the Israeli rescue force that freed the abductees and shows how they cut a hole in the wall to reach the house where the abductees were located.

Ali Hamed, who was killed yesterday 👆 in the attack on the "Wahid" station in southern Lebanon, received the "seal of approval" of Hezbollah.

Number 336

The "hot" story of Saturday for the Palestinians in the West Bank was not the release of the abductees in Nuseirat...

What drew a lot of interest on social networks was a video of a swimming pool in Ramallah (probably in one of the villas) in which mixed swimming was observed between men and women in swimwear, in a style that is not usually the first choice for Muslim women...

Many complaints reached the PA police, who dispatched their officers to the scene and closed the pool due to "violation of morals".

Gazans, for their part, lamented that while they are counting more than 200 dead in Nuseirat, their brothers (and sisters) in the West Bank are spending time at pool parties...
Supersonic booms over the Dahieh district in Beirut, Hezbollah's stronghold in the Lebanese capital, reported an hour ago.

A photo sent to me by the follower R. in which we see Sergeant Saif Bisan who was killed in battle in the Gaza Strip on April 9, 2008. In an operation of the "Egoz" unit in the south of the Gaza Strip, near the Kissufim crossing, together with his friend Arnon Zamora, who was killed yesterday in the operation to rescue the hostages. Arnon is the one with the big smile on the right side of the picture.

Sometime during their course in 2005.
2 heroes.

Hamas Information Bureau:
226 dead and more than 400 wounded arrived yesterday at the Shuhada al-Aqsa and Al-Awda hospitals in the center of the Gaza Strip.

Rafah sector: Palestinian reports of tank fire and attacks in north-eastern Rafah

This morning, Palestinians reported an exchange of fire between Israeli tanks and Hamas operatives in the neighborhoods of Khirbat al-Adas and al-Misabah (both circled in red).

After establishing its hold on the south-western part of Rafah, adjacent to the Philadelphia axis (south of the blue line in the attached map), and expanding its control near the coast, it is evident that the IDF is preparing to expand its reach towards the north-east (in the direction of the blue arrows).

Toronto: Canadian police officers in shorts fold the Palestinian flag in the middle of an anti-Israeli demonstration. The one coming in from the right would make a skilled boxer...

The crowd in response: Shame. shame.

The Palestinians on social media are angry about the celebrations and fireworks in Jordan yesterday on the occasion of the 25th anniversary of the coronation of Abdullah the King of Jordan, while they are counting their dead in Nuseirat following the operation to rescue the kidnapped.

Senior Hamas official Muhammad Mardawi:

There are steps we are taking now to prevent the possibility of another Israeli operation like the one in Nuseirat.

The US Central Command did not forget to congratulate the Israeli security forces and the Israeli people on the occasion of the hostage rescue operation.

##
Thank you very much 🇮🇱🇺🇸❤️
The Americans are worried that following the Palestinian claims, Hamas operatives will attack the pier.

Further to this video👆, in which a rescue helicopter is seen landing near the American floating dock during the operation to rescue the hostages, the US Central Command publishes a clarification:

The humanitarian pier... was not used in the operation to rescue hostages.

The pier's sole purpose is to bring lifesaving assistance into Gaza.

##
In another publication on behalf of the US Central Command, it was stated that about 492 tons of aid were brought into the Gaza Strip yesterday through the pier, after it was put back in place yesterday.
